    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "\n\n# Problem: \nwhen using the -u flag to point to a different init.vim file, nvim loads the correct file, but this is not acknowledged in either `:checkhealth` nor does `:e $MYVIMRC` point to it. \n\nThis makes it difficult to know if it's actually loading a different config, or if changes to the config are loaded. This is especially true if you are loading variations of the config file for testing (Is the init file loaded, is it a plugin problem, or a syntax error?).  \n\nIf you don't have a init.vim in the default folder, `:checkhealth` has a \"Missing config\" error, which makes it even more confusing. \n\n# Solution:\nHave $MYVIMRC and `:checkhealth` register the new init file and have nvim treat it as the default for the session.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "From [:help starting]\r\n```\r\n\tIf Nvim was started with \"-u {file}\" then {file} is used as the config\r\n\tand all initializations until 5. are skipped. $MYVIMRC is not set.\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis is expected behavior, and is identical between vim and neovim. But I would agree with OP that it would be intuitive to set `$MYVIMRC` in these cases.\r\n\r\nIf maintainers agree, change would be somewhere here: https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/master/src/nvim/main.c#L1878-L1880",
